  "text": "The historical definitions for types of parallel computers [CITATION_1] are outdated [CITATION_2] . To reflect this fact, architectures are referred to here as shared-memory, where multiple processors have access to a single memory block, or distributed-memory, where each processor has its own block of memory. A third architecture is now common due to multicore processors, where multiple processing cores on a single processor have access to a single block of memory but not to the memory of other processors; this configuration is sometimes termed a hybrid architecture.",
